    {
      "id": "cb33667a013915860a3821f6f9429a1c0dbfc995",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 117,
        "name": "Andreas Dilger",
        "email": "adilger@thelustrecollective.com",
        "username": "adilger"
      },
      "date": "2011-10-19 22:18:42.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n\n(7 inline comments)\n\nNeeds some cleanups before landing.\n\nThe other question I have about this is whether there is a compatibility issue with disabling ACLs?  I know in the past that disabling ACLs caused some buffers to not be used, and that confused clients, which is why we always enabled ACLs at the network protocol level.\n\nPerhaps the code always sends the ACL buffers today, but they are zero length?",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
    {
      "id": "c370109928d109af87d3ffb5420ef8016b9c500f",
      "author": {
        "_account_id": 3,
        "name": "Fan Yong",
        "email": "fan.yong@intel.com",
        "username": "nasf",
        "inactive": true
      },
      "date": "2011-10-25 06:21:23.000000000",
      "message": "Patch Set 7:\n\n> Patch Set 7: I would prefer that you didn't submit this\n(7 inline comments)\n> Needs some cleanups before landing.\n> The other question I have about this is whether there is a compatibility issue with disabling ACLs? I know in the past that disabling ACLs caused some buffers to not be used, and that confused clients, which is why we always enabled ACLs at the network protocol level.\nPerhaps the code always sends the ACL buffers today, but they are zero length?\n\nI have test sanity for patch without ACL, works well. In fact, in currently master implementation, the ACL field is exist, but its length is flexible, if disable ACL, it will be set as zero always.",
      "accounts_in_message": [],
      "_revision_number": 7
    },
